Key.Paste: If a used needle can transmit HIV, why can't a mosquito? Laurence Corash, chief medical officer of Cerus Corporation, provides the following explanation: The AIDS virus (HIV) on used needles is infectious when injected into a human where the virus can bind to T cell and start to replicate. The human T cell is a very specific host cell for HIV. When a mosquito feeds on a person with HIV in his or her blood, the HIV enters the insect's gut, which does not contain human T

Hydroxiurea in patients with sickle cell syndromes followed up at Hospital Hemope, Recife-PE
Sicke cell syndromes (SCS)consist of a set of qualitative hemoglobin diseases, in which the S hemoglobin gene is inherited.(1) Out of these syndromes, the most frequent one is the sickle cell anemia (homozygosis SS) whose patients have presented organ damages since childhood, as a result from repeated vessel-occlusive episodes.(2) Several studies in adults have been showing the efficiency of the use of hydroxiurea (HU), whose main effect is the increase in the fetal hemoglobin levels (HbF) in patients carriers of SCS with little or no side effect. (3,4,5,6) HU is a well known chemotherapeutic agent and it is used in the treatment of myeloproliferative syndromes such as acute myeloid leukemia and polycitemia vera. Its main function is the DNA synthesis blocking by inhibiting the ribonucleotide reductase , keeping the cells at S phase. (1) It is easy to use, with few toxic effects and with a myelosuppressor effect easily revertible. The use of hydroxiurea in the protocols of sickle cell anemia (SCA) treatment began in the 80's, in adult patients, later its use was authorized in children. Over the years, studies in children have been showing equal efficiency of HU without great side effects. (2,7,8,9,10) Thus, the present study aimed, based on several cases, to investigate the efficiency and the tolerance to the use of HU by patients carriers of SCS at pediatric and young adults age range, as well as to assess variations of hematologic parameters in both age range and of the Hb F values, in the pediatric group.
